# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: daniel-c-drucker
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Previously at the University of California, Berkeley, he served as the 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory from 2009 to 2016, as interim vice chancellor for research from 2016 to 2017, and as executive vice chancellor and provost from 2017 to 2021.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] His academic research focuses on nanomaterials, particularly nanocrystal fabrication for biomedical and renewable energy applications.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Paul Alivisatos was born in Chicago, Illinois, where he lived until the age of 10, when his family moved to Athens, Greece.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He returned to the United States to attend the University of Chicago in the late 1970s.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos received a Bachelor of Arts degree (with honors) with a major in chemistry from the University of Chicago in 1981 and a Ph.D. in physical chemistry from the University of California, Berkeley, in 1986.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] His doctoral advisor at Berkeley was Charles B.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] His doctoral thesis was titled *The photophysical properties of molecules near metal and semiconductor surfaces*.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] After receiving his doctorate, Alivisatos joined AT&T Bell Labs working with Louis E.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Brus, and began research in the field of nanotechnology.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos returned to the University of California, Berkeley in 1988 as an assistant professor of chemistry.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He was promoted to associate professor in 1993 and to full professor in 1995.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] In administrative roles, Alivisatos served as the 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory from 2009 to 2016, as the university's interim vice chancellor for research from 2016 to 2017, and as executive vice chancellor and provost from 2017 to 2021.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] In August 2013, he was appointed as Samsung Distinguished Professor in Nanoscience and Nanotechnology Research.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He was also the founding director of the Kavli Energy Nanosciences Institute (ENSI).
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos joined the Materials Sciences Division at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in 1991.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He served as associate laboratory director for physical sciences from 2005 to 2007.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] In 2008, he became deputy director, and he stepped in as interim director after Steven Chu left to become United States Secretary of Energy under the first Obama administration.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] On November 19, 2009, Alivisatos was appointed 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He refocused the lab on renewable energy and climate research, oversaw new facilities, deepened ties to the national innovation ecosystem, and advanced collaborations that sped technology transfer across industries from autos to medicine.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] On March 23, 2015, he announced that he would step down from the directorship once a successor was named.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] On February 26, 2021, the Board of Trustees of the University of Chicago named Alivisatos as the incoming 14th president of the University of Chicago, with his term beginning on September 1, 2021.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He succeeded Robert Zimmer, who served as the university president from July 2006 to August 2021.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition to the office of the president, he was named the John D.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] MacArthur Distinguished Service Professor, chair of the Board of Governors of Argonne National Laboratory, and chair of the Board of Directors of Fermi Forward Discovery Group LLC, which operates the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] On September 24, 2025, the Board of Trustees of the University of Chicago extended Alivisatos's presidency through June 2030.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is an internationally recognized authority on nano chemistry in the synthesis of semiconductor quantum dots and multi-shaped artificial nanostructures.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Further, he is a world expert on the chemistry of nanoscale crystals; one of his papers (Science, 271: 933–937, 1996) has been cited over 13,800 times.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He is also an expert on how these can be applied, for example as biological markers (e.g., Science, 281: 2013–16, 1998; a paper cited over 10,900 times).
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition, his use of DNA in this area (DNA nanotechnology) has shown the surprising versatility of this molecule.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He has used it to direct crystal growth and create new materials, as in Nature, 382: 609–11, 1996, and even to measure nanoscale distances (see Nature Nanotechnology, 1: 47–52, 2006).
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] In February 2011, Alivisatos was ranked fifth among the world's top 100 chemists for the period 2000–2010 in the list released by Thomson Reuters.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He is widely recognized as being the first to demonstrate that semiconductor nanocrystals can be grown into complex two-dimensional shapes, as opposed to simple one-dimensional spheres.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos proved that controlling the growth of nanocrystals is the key to controlling both their size and shape.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] This achievement altered the nanoscience landscape and paved the way for a slew of new potential applications, including biomedical diagnostics, revolutionary photovoltaic cells, and LED materials.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Given that a nanocrystal is virtually all surface and no interior, its properties can vary considerably as the crystal grows in size.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Prior to Alivisatos's research, all non-metal nanocrystals were dot-shaped, meaning they were essentially one-dimensional.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] No techniques had been reported for making two-dimensional or rod-shaped semiconductor nanocrystals that would also be of uniform size.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] However, in a landmark paper that appeared in the March 2, 2000, issue of the journal Nature, Alivisatos reported on techniques used to select the size but vary the shapes of the nanocrystals produced.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] This was hailed as a major breakthrough in nanocrystal fabrication because rod-shaped semiconductor nanocrystals can be stacked to create nano-sized electronic devices.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos went on to use his techniques to create an entirely new generation of hybrid solar cells that combined nanotechnology with plastic electronics.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is the founding scientist of Quantum Dot Corporation, a company that makes crystalline nanoscale tags that are used in the study of cell behavior.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] (Quantum Dot is now part of Life Technologies.) He also founded the nanotechnology company Nanosys, and Solexant, a photovoltaic start-up that has since restarted as Siva Power.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is the founding editor of *Nano Letters*, a publication of the American Chemical Society.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He formerly served on the Senior Editorial Board of *Science*.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He has also served on the editorial advisory boards of*ACS Nano*, the *Journal of Physical Chemistry*, *Chemical Physics*, the *Journal of Chemical Physics*, and *Advanced Materials*.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition to those listed above, Alivisatos has held fellowships with the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the American Physical Society (1996), and the American Chemical Society.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] He is a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is married to Nicole Alivisatos, a retired chemist, former editor of the journal Nano Letters, and daughter of the noted chemist, Gábor A.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Abel Wolman was born to Louis and Rose Wachsman Wolman on June 10, 1892 in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] He was the fourth eldest child of Polish-Jewish immigrants.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Wolman received his high school education from the Baltimore City College in 1909.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Following his high school education, Wolman received his Bachelor of Arts in 1913 as a pre-med major.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Although Wolman was interested in becoming a doctor, his mother's insistence on studying engineering led him to pursue a degree in engineering.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] He then went on to complete a Bachelor of Science in Engineering at the Johns Hopkins University, graduating in 1915 as the fourth person to receive a degree at the newly-established Whiting School of Engineering.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Although Wolman did not complete a doctorate degree, his work in the field of sanitary engineering led to him being awarded an honorary Doctor of Engineering in 1937.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Wolman was also awarded a Doctor of Humane Letters from the Maryland Institute College of Arts and a Doctor of Law by the Johns Hopkins University in 1969.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Wolman served an extensive career in sanitary engineering, working in both environmental and public health services as well as in academics.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1914, he started his long career in public health as an assistant engineer working for the United States Public Health Service.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1922, Wolman became the Chief Engineer of the Maryland State Department of Health, where he served for 18 years until 1939.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] While working in the public health sector, Wolman conducted research related to sanitation and public health.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] He is best known for his 1919 contribution, with chemist Linn Enslow, in the standardization of chlorinating Baltimore's drinking-water supply.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] His efforts there helped develop the plan for Baltimore's water supply so thoroughly and effectively that it remains well-provided for growth through the 21st century.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] His work also benefited water systems in New York, Detroit and Columbus, Ohio.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] At that same time, he served as the Department of Sanitary Engineering's chairman until his official retirement in 1962.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] During his time as a sanitary engineering lecturer, he was asked to lecture at many prestigious universities, including Harvard University, Princeton University, University of Southern California, and University of Chicago.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] He was appointed Professor Emeritus in 1962, but had no desire to retire from professional life, so he continued his teaching and research in addition to serving as a consultant to the many governments and municipalities that requested his advice and assistance.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Supplementing his professional life, Wolman also held many important positions in the committees of professional societies and journal publications.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1916, he joined the American Public Health Association as an associate editor of the organization's monthly publication, *American Journal of Public Health,* where he eventually became the editor in 1955 until 1957.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Within the American Public Health Association, Wolman served as Chairman of the Public Health Engineering Section and Chairman of the Committee on Research and Standards.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Through their marriage, Wolman had one son, named Markley (M.) Gordon Wolman.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Maintaining a lively and witty personality, Wolman was favorable amongst many of the students he interacted with as a professor.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] From colleagues and family members that knew Wolman well, he has been described as being very well-organized and always perceptive towards his problems and analyses related to work.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Wolman died at his home in Baltimore, Maryland on February 22, 1989, aged 96 years old.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In collaboration with Linn Enslow, Wolman wanted to standardize a chlorination method to purify municipal water supplies.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] At the time, the purification of water with chlorine was known and employed in cities, but the problem that Wolman and Enslow highlighted in this publication was that the dosage of chlorine used by cities were unreliable and unscientific.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] As a result, municipal water supplies were often incorrectly purified, leading to failures in performance marked by diseases.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Wolman and Enslow began their experiment by describing their observations on the rate of chlorine absorption in different water samples that varied in bacteria, color, turbidity, oxidizable compounds, and other purity factors.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In "The Metabolism of Cities", Wolman highlighted three major "metabolic" problems that plagued major cities in the United States and offered his insight on the reality of those problems and possible solutions.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] He defined the metabolic requirements of a city as all materials and commodities needed to sustain its population, including all processes related to the proper removal and disposal of waste products produced in daily life.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] However, he pointed out that many major US cities share three metabolic problems: (1) lack of an adequate water supply, (2) ineffective disposal of sewage, and (3) poor control of air pollution.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Throughout most of the paper, Wolman provided relevant statistics and figures to underscore the proposed metabolic problems and analyzed historical municipal proposals designed to alleviate those metabolic problems.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] He concluded the article on a somewhat optimistic note, mentioning that the future of water sanitation, sewage disposal, and eliminating air pollutants is hopeful.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] However, in order to reach that future, Wolman called for immediate action and planning of policies and programs needed to combat the three metabolic problems.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Since the publication of this paper, there have been many studies performed to develop viable solutions to tackle the water shortages, waste disposal, and air pollution issues proposed by Wolman.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] For example, in 1999, civil and environmental engineers at the University of California, Berkeley published a research paper that confirmed the presence of water shortages in the United States and advocated for cities to take water recycling and reuse measures.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] For his efforts in public health practices and engineering skills on a local and global level, Wolman was granted multiple awards.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1948, Wolman was awarded the Sedgwick Memorial Medal by the American Public Health Association for his contributions in the field of public health.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1960, he was awarded the Albert Lasker Special Award in Public Health, which is an award "for outstanding contributions in research related to diseases which are the main causes of death and disability and for distinguished service in the field of public health administration.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1967, Wolman was awarded the William Procter Prize for Scientific Achievement for his contributions in the field of science.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1968, Wolman was awarded the first Lewis L.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1973, Wolman was awarded the Milton Stover Eisenhower Medal.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1974, Wolman was awarded the National Medal of Science.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1976, Wolman was awarded the Tyler Prize for Environmental Achievement and the Ben Gurion Award.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Both in 1973 and 1977, Wolman was awarded the American Water Works Association Award.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1986, Wolman was awarded the Robert E.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Horton Medal and the John Wesley Powell Award.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Finally, in 1999, The Baltimore Sun named Wolman "Marylander of the Century".
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] Following the death of Wolman, multiple tributes were created in his honor.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] For individuals that work in the water industry, the American Water Works Association annually presents the Abel Wolman Award of Excellence since 1985.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In May 1966, the Johns Hopkins University named a newly acquired dormitory Wolman Hall, which continues to house first year students.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/abel-wolman] In 1986, the City of Baltimore renamed its public works building to the Abel Wolman Municipal Building, honoring his years of service to the city.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] Bovik received a Primetime Emmy Award in 2015 for his development of perception-based video quality measurement tools that are now standards in television production.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] Al Bovik was educated at the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign (PhD 1984).
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] He has made numerous fundamental contributions to the fields of digital photography, digital television, digital image processing, digital video processing, digital cinema, and computational visual perception.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] He is particularly well known for his work on low-level vision, natural scene modeling, image quality, and video quality.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] He has published more than 1000 technical articles, books, and patents in these areas.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] Overall, his work has been cited in the scientific and engineering literature more than 200,000 times according to Google Scholar.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] He is one of the most highly cited engineers in the world according to the Web of Science.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] Bovik is an elected member of the United States National Academy of Engineering (NAE), an elected Foreign Fellow of the Indian National Academy of Engineering (INAE), an elected Fellow of the U.S.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] National Academy of Inventors, and an elected foreign member of Academia Europaea (2023).
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] He is also a Life Fellow of the IEEE, a Fellow of Optica and of the Society of Photo-Optical and Instrumentation Engineers (SPIE), an Honorary Fellow of the Royal Photographic Society (HonFRPS) and an Honorary Member of the Society for Imaging Science and Technology (IS&T).
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] He is a voting member of the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences (Television Academy) and was named an inaugural member of its Science and Technology Peer Group.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] He was named a Distinguished Alumnus of the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign in 2008.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] His high-dynamic range (HDR) add-on model HDRMAX, which improves the quality prediction performance of leading models is marketed and used worldwide.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] He was the founder and First General Chair of the IEEE International Conference on Image Processing (ICIP).
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] He also co-founded (with David Munson, Jr.) the IEEE Transactions on Image Processing and was its longest-serving Editor-in-Chief, with a tenure of six years.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] Bovik's academic legacy includes serving as the supervising professor of more than 70 PhD graduates, more than 50 master's degree recipients, and more than two dozen post-doctoral researchers.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] His award-winning online courseware is used internationally: SIVA – Courseware for Signal, Image, Video and Audio Processing.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] This online courseware offers online curricula for digital image and video processing and digital signal processing.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] SIVA includes hundreds of signal, image and video processing demonstrations delivering live, interactive audio-visual experiences of signal and image processing algorithms.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-bovik] Bovik has received a number of major international awards.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] Needleman received his B.S. from the University of Pennsylvania in 1966, an M.S. and Ph.D. from Harvard University in 1967 and 1970 respectively, advised by John W.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] He was an instructor and assistant professor in the Department of Applied Mathematics at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology from 1970 to 1975.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] He was a professor of engineering at Brown University starting in 1975, and served as the dean of the Engineering Department from 1988 to 1991.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] He was the chair of the Applied Mechanics Division.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] Needleman's main research interests are in the computational modeling of deformation and fracture processes in structural materials, in particular metals.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] A general objective is to provide quantitative relations between the measurable (and hopefully controllable) features of the materials' micro-scale structure and its macroscopic mechanical behavior.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] Ongoing research projects involve studies of ductile fracture and ductile-brittle transitions; crack growth in heterogeneous microstructures with particular emphasis on the role of interfaces; nonlocal and discrete dislocation plasticity; fatigue crack growth; and fast fracture in brittle solids.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] Professor Needleman often collaborates with Viggo Tvergaard, John Hutchinson, Subra Suresh, and Erik van der Giessen among others in both materials science and mechanics.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] He has been recognized by Institute for Scientific Information (ISI) Science Citation Index as a highly cited author both in engineering and in materials science.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] In 1994, his work on 3D modeling of metallic fracture was a finalist in the Science Category for the Computerworld-Smithsonian Award.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] In 2006 he was the recipient of both the William Prager Medal and the Drucker Medal and received an Honorary Doctorate from Technical University of Denmark (DTU).
[src:daniel-c-drucker/alan-needleman] He is also the recipient of Timoshenko Medal in 2011.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:daniel-c-drucker/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:daniel-c-drucker/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] Drucker was known as an authority on the theory of plasticity in the field of applied mechanics.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] His key contributions to the field of plasticity include the concept of material stability described by the Drucker stability postulates and the Drucker–Prager yield criterion.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] His father Moses Abraham Drucker was a civil engineer, and Drucker wanted to follow in his footsteps.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] Drucker studied at the Columbia University, where he obtained his BSc in civil engineering in 1938.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] Next, in 1940 he obtained his PhD in mechanical engineering under Raymond D.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] Between 1940 and 1943, Drucker taught at Cornell University, later joining the Armour Research Foundation.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] Army Air Corps service, he briefly returned to the Illinois Institute of Technology, then he taught at Brown University from 1946 until 1968 when he joined the University of Illinois as Dean of Engineering.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] In 1984 he left Illinois to become a graduate research professor at the University of Florida until his retirement in 1994.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] He received the Murray Lecture and Award in 1967, title the seventh Honorary Member in 1969, Frocht Award in 1971 and title of Fellow from the Society for Strain Analysis (SESA), now known as the Society for Experimental Mechanics (SEM).
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] In 1988, Drucker was awarded the National Medal of Science.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] He was a member of the National Academy of Engineering and of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] The Drucker Medal is named in his honor.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] He was also awarded the ASME Timoshenko Medal in 1983 and the ASME Robert Henry Thurston Lecture Award in 1986.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] Drucker Medal, awarded by the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, was named in his honor in 1998.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] Drucker was the first recipient of this annual award.
[src:daniel-c-drucker/daniel-c-drucker] Drucker died from leukemia on September 1, 2001.
